Task: Find all integer solutions to the Diophantine equation
42x − 91y = 77


Solution:

1. Compute gcd and simplify the equation  
   The greatest common divisor of 42 and 91 is  
   gcd(42, 91) = 7.  
   Divide the whole equation by 7:
       42x − 91y = 77  
       6x − 13y = 11.          (1)

2. Find one particular integer solution of (1)  
   We want integers x, y such that
       6x − 13y = 11.

   Work modulo 13:
       6x ≡ 11 (mod 13).

   The inverse of 6 modulo 13 is 11, because
       6 · 11 = 66 ≡ 1 (mod 13).

   Multiply both sides of 6x ≡ 11 (mod 13) by 11:
       x ≡ 11 · 11 ≡ 121 ≡ 4 (mod 13).

   So one solution is x = 4. Put x = 4 into (1):
       6·4 − 13y = 11  
       24 − 13y = 11  
       13 = 13y  
       y = 1.

   Thus (x0, y0) = (4, 1) is a particular solution.

3. Describe all integer solutions  
   The homogeneous equation to (1) is
       6x − 13y = 0.

   A direction solution can be found by solving 6x = 13y.  
   One simple choice is x = 13, y = 6. So every solution of  
   the homogeneous equation has the form
       (x, y) = (13t, 6t),  t ∈ ℤ.

   Therefore, all integer solutions of (1) are
       (x, y) = (4, 1) + (13t, 6t)  
              = (4 + 13t, 1 + 6t),  t ∈ ℤ.

   So all integer solutions of the original equation are
       x = 4 + 13t,  
       y = 1 + 6t,  
       where t is any integer.

4. Find the solution with the smallest x > 100  
   We need
       x = 4 + 13t > 100.

   This inequality gives
       13t > 96  
       t > 96/13 ≈ 7.38.

   The smallest integer t that satisfies this is t = 8.

   For t = 8:
       x = 4 + 13·8 = 4 + 104 = 108,  
       y = 1 + 6·8 = 1 + 48 = 49.

   Check in the original equation:
       42·108 − 91·49 = 4536 − 4459 = 77

   So the solution with the smallest x that is greater than 100 is
       [108, 49].
